1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 {A flexible move, aimed at maintaining a
harmonious developing course.} (4. Nbd2 {will be the subject of a different
database.}) 4... Qe7 {This is a flexible move, maintaining the tension for a
while, as Bxb4 would lose a pawn to ...Qxb4+. Black's main plan is to
stabilize on the dark squares with ...d7-d6 and ...e6-e5, revealing the
queen's usefulness on e7. In some lines, Black can use the square d8 to
retreat with his c6-knight. Not least, delaying the exchange on d2 is likely
to force White to make a small concession.} (4... Bxd2+ {is premature as White
can reach an optimal setup with} 5. Qxd2 d6 6. Nc3 {, followed by g2-g3. After
4...Qe7 it will not be that simple for White to take on d2 with the queen and
develop the knight to c3.}) (4... a5 {allows White to remove the pin in time.}
5. g3 d6 (5... d5 {is a viable line, but this article is based on displaying
the pawns on the dark squares, in genuine Bogo spirit.} 6. Bg2 dxc4 7. Qc2 Nc6
8. Qxc4 Qd5 9. Qd3 Qe4) 6. Bg2 Nc6 7. O-O e5 8. Bg5 $1 {Due to the threat
a2-a3, Black has to play} exd4 9. Nxd4 {, leaving White with a space advantage
in a half-open position.}) 5. Nc3 {In this section we will examine a few rare
lines, some of which could transpose below. The last move is a try to switch
to a Nimzo-Indian. True, Bd2 is a bit unusual, but so is ...Qe7, at least at
this stage.} (5. e3 {This is a rare move at high level. White develops
normally but does not exert any pressure in the centre.} O-O 6. Bd3 ({If} 6.
Bxb4 Qxb4+ 7. Qd2 {Black can transpose to the normal lines below with} Qe7 {
, but the queen exchange should also be fine.}) 6... Bxd2+ (6... b6 {is
entirely possible, but we will follow the same plan as in the main lines.}) 7.
Qxd2 {The most active answer, as the knight is best placed on c3.} (7. Nbxd2 {
frees Black of early worries regarding the square d5.} d6 8. O-O e5 9. dxe5
dxe5 10. Ne4 Nxe4 11. Bxe4 f5 12. Bc2 Rd8 13. Qe2 e4 14. Nd4 c5 15. Nb5 Nc6 16.
Nc3 Be6 {Black has comfortable development. Without the dark-squared bishops,
the invasion on d5 can be answered with a blockading plan.} 17. Nd5 Bxd5 18.
cxd5 Ne5 19. Rad1 Rd6 20. f3 exf3 21. gxf3 g6 {, with at least equal play for
Black. Mons,L (2544)-Meier,G (2623) chess.com INT 2019 (1/2-1/2, 44)}) 7... d6
8. Qc3 (8. Nc3 {looks more natural but offers Black free play:} e5 9. Bc2 Bg4
$5 10. O-O-O $5 Nbd7 11. h3 Bxf3 12. gxf3 a6 {, planning ...b7-b5 with
counterplay.}) 8... Re8 9. Nbd2 e5 10. e4 exd4 11. Nxd4 d5 (11... c5 12. Ne2
Nc6 $11) 12. O-O c5 13. cxd5 $5 {Otherwise White would be just slightly worse.}
cxd4 14. Qxd4 Rd8 15. Qc3 Nbd7 16. Rfe1 Ne5 17. Be2 Bd7 18. Qd4 {In Shankland,
S (2713)-Cori, J (2686) Biel 2019 (1/2-1/2, 40) White only had some
compensation for the piece at this stage. The simplest way to keep things
under control was} g5 $5 $17) (5. Qb3 {forces the exchange without wasting a
tempo on a2-a3, but after} Bxd2+ 6. Nbxd2 d6 {the queen is not too well placed
on b3, either.}) (5. Bxb4 {loses a pawn for some abstract compensation.} Qxb4+
6. Qd2 (6. Nbd2 Qxb2) 6... Qxc4 {Black's compact structure entitles him to
rely on completing development and keeping the extra pawn.}) ({The main move,} 
5. g3 {, is the subject of all the lines below.}) 5... Bxc3 {This is by far
not the only good move. But it makes sense to follow the same plan as in the
main lines below.} ({Some might prefer} 5... b6 {, reaching a comfortable
Nimzo-Queen's-Indian hybrid.}) 6. Bxc3 Ne4 7. Qc2 (7. Rc1 d6 8. g3 (8. e3 {
has never been tried but is not challenging} O-O 9. Bd3 Nxc3 10. Rxc3 e5 $11)
8... Nc6 {transposes to lines 14-17.}) 7... Nxc3 8. Qxc3 d6 9. e4 {The most
ambitious of the sidelines.} (9. e3 {is more modest.} O-O 10. Be2 Re8 11. O-O
e5 12. b4 Bg4 13. h3 Bh5 14. Rfe1 a5 15. b5 Nd7 16. Rac1 exd4 (16... b6 $2 {
Gurvich,V (2280)-Tregubov,P (2588) Moscow 2018 (0-1, 64) allows the trick} 17.
Nxe5 $1 Bxe2 18. Nc6 $16) 17. exd4 Qf6 {[%cal Gd7f8] , followed by ...Nf8-e6,
with good counterplay on the dark squares .}) (9. g3 Nc6 {transposes to lines
12 and 13.}) 9... O-O 10. Bd3 c5 ({The neutral} 10... Nd7 {is also playable:}
11. O-O (11. e5 dxe5 12. dxe5 Nc5 13. Bc2 a5 14. O-O b6 $11) 11... e5 12. b4 a5
13. a3 axb4 14. axb4 Rxa1 15. Rxa1 exd4 16. Nxd4 Qf6 $11) 11. O-O (11. dxc5
dxc5 12. e5 Bd7 13. h4 Nc6 14. Rd1 Rfd8 15. Bb1 Be8 16. O-O Rxd1 17. Rxd1 Rd8
18. Rxd8 Qxd8 19. Qc2 g6 20. Qd3 Nd4 21. Nxd4 cxd4 $15 {Batsiashvili,N (2504)
-Tregubov,P (2575) Caleta 2018 (1/2-1/2, 47)}) (11. d5 e5 $5 {allows Black to
reach the blocked structure.}) 11... cxd4 (11... Nd7 $5 12. Rfe1 e5 {Both
knights are far away from the critical d5 and d4 squares, but Black has the
"good" bishop.} 13. dxe5 (13. dxc5 Nxc5 $5 $11) 13... dxe5 (13... Nxe5 $5 $11)
14. Bc2 f6 15. Nh4 Nb8 16. Ba4 {White should not allow ...Nc6-d4.} Rd8 17. Rad1
Rd4 $11) (11... Nc6 12. d5 {gains some time for White.}) 12. Nxd4 e5 13. Nc2
Be6 14. Qd2 Nc6 15. Rad1 Rfd8 16. Rfe1 Rac8 17. Bf1 h6 $11 {Karnaukh,A (2277)
-Panchenko,A (2395) Kiev 2003 (1/2-1/2, 65) Black is very solid and the square
d4 is no less important than its correspondent square d5.} *

