1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. a3 {Surprisingly, this is the
second most popular move after 5.g3.White forces Black to release the tension
at once. In some cases, a2-a3 could be useful, but at this stage it looks like
a small waste of time and a weakening of the light squares.} Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 {
In principle, this is the only move to justify the early a2-a3, as White can
play the desirable Nc3 next.} (6. Nfxd2 {has the same idea, but it looks a bit
like a counter developing move.} d6 7. Nc3 O-O 8. e3 e5 9. dxe5 {Trying to
justify the knight's presence on d2 due to its control over e4.} (9. Be2 {
allows Black to simplify with easy play:} exd4 10. exd4 {With the knight on d2,
...Nxd4 is not available.} Bg4 11. O-O Bxe2 12. Nxe2 Nc6 {[%cal Gd6d5] ,
planning ... d6-d5.} 13. d5 Ne5 $11) (9. d5 {was played in a couple of games,
and now the most active plan is} Ne8 $146 {[%cal Gf7f5] , preparing ...f7-f5.})
9... dxe5 10. Qc2 Be6 11. Bd3 Nbd7 12. b4 a5 13. Rb1 axb4 14. axb4 c5 15. b5
Ra3 16. O-O Rfa8 {1/2-1/2 (33) Soural,J (2169)-Kuba,S (2246) Czechia 2002}) ({
For some reason, the most popular move now is} 6. Nbxd2 {examined in Line 3.})
6... d6 7. Nc3 O-O 8. e4 {This prevents a later ...e5-e4 but weakens d4.} (8.
e3 e5 {Threatening ...e5-e4, when the knight would not have good squares.} 9.
Qc2 Bg4 10. dxe5 {Trying to get active play.} (10. Be2 {does not prepare
serious problems for Black:} Nbd7 11. O-O e4 $5 12. Nd2 Bxe2 13. Nxe2 Rfe8 14.
b4 c6 15. a4 d5 $11) 10... dxe5 11. Ng5 c6 12. h3 Bc8 $5 $146 {The bishop is
safe here and Black will get his wasted time back after ...h7-h6.} 13. Be2 (13.
b4 {is premature due to White's incomplete development.} a5 14. Rb1 axb4 15.
axb4 h6 16. Nf3 Na6 $15 {If White defends b4, Black can get control of the
dark squares with ...c6-c5 while if} 17. c5 b6 $1 18. cxb6 $6 Nxb4 19. Qb3 c5
$17 {, dooming the pawn on b6.}) 13... h6 14. Nge4 (14. Nf3 e4 15. Nd4 c5 16.
Nb3 b6 $11) 14... Nxe4 15. Nxe4 f5 $11 {, with active play.}) (8. g3 {
transposes to Line 4.}) 8... e5 9. d5 (9. dxe5 {offers White only a temporary
initiative, while the weakness on d4 will be permanent.} dxe5 10. Nd5 {
Otherwise the exchange on e5 would not have any justification.} Qd8 $1 (10...
Qd6 {allows White to gain a tempo with} 11. c5 $1) 11. Bd3 (11. O-O-O {does
not make a big difference.} c6 12. Nc3 Qa5 13. Be2 Bg4 14. Nh4 Bxe2 15. Qxe2
Nbd7 16. Nf5 Nc5 17. Rd6 Ne6 18. Qe3 Rad8 19. Rhd1 {Vilerte,T (2234)-Dittmar,P
(2338) Triesen 2008 (0-1, 60)} g6 $1 $146 {White will soon lose stability.})
11... c6 12. Nxf6+ Qxf6 13. Qc3 Re8 14. c5 Nd7 15. O-O Nf8 16. Nd2 Ne6 $11 {
0-1 (21) Clijsen,M (2172)-Ikonnikov,V (2525) Netherlands 2012}) (9. Bd3 {
fails to maintain the tension under favourable circumstances.} Bg4 10. d5 (10.
Qe3 Bxf3 11. gxf3 Nc6 $11) 10... Bxf3 11. gxf3 Nh5 $15 {Tello,Y-Arkell,K (2457)
London 2001 (0-1, 35)}) 9... a5 {Delaying b2-b4 and creating the potential
threat of blocking the queenside with ... a5-a4.} 10. b3 {The most principled
move, costing White another developing tempo, though.} (10. Bd3 Bg4 11. Qe3 Na6
12. Nd2 (12. O-O Nc5 13. Bc2 a4 $11) 12... Nc5 13. Be2 (13. b3 Nh5 {offers
Black counterplay, as if} 14. g3 $2 Nf4 $1 {is possible anyway:} 15. gxf4 exf4
16. Qd4 Qe5 17. Qxe5 Nxd3+ $17) 13... a4 14. O-O Bd7 $11 {Ljamin,V (2143)
-Novichkov,V (2371) Moscow 2013 (1/2-1/2, 51)}) (10. Be2 Nbd7 11. O-O Nc5 12.
Qc2 a4 13. Nd2 Bd7 $11 14. b4 axb3 15. Nxb3 Ba4 16. Nxa4 Nxa4 $15 {Voiteanu,C 
(2313)-Ikonnikov,V (2553) Campobasso 2011 (0-1, 33)}) 10... Na6 11. Bd3 {
This looks active, but leaves the knight on f3 exposed.} (11. Be2 Nc5 12. Qc2
Nh5 13. O-O f5 $15 {Hernandez Garcia,J-Ulybin,M (2575) Corte Ingles 1998 (0-1,
22)}) (11. b4 $2 {leaves White hanging after} axb4 12. axb4 Bg4 $17 {,
attacking b4 and threatening ...Bxf3.}) 11... Bg4 12. Qe3 Nh5 13. O-O Nf4 14.
Bc2 {Osterman,R (2415)-Boensch,U (2490) Bad Woerishofen 1993 (1/2-1/2, 69)} f5
$11 {, with normal counterplay.} *

