Kasoshvili,T (2106)-Arabidze,M (2374) Lagodekhi 2016 (0-1, 33)}) 9... dxe5 10.
O-O c5 $5 {Preparing ...e5-e4 without allwoing Nd4.} ({But} 10... e4 {is
entirely possible as well:} 11. Nd4 c5 12. Nb5 Nc6 13. Qb3 Bf5 14. Rfd1 h5 15.
Nf1 b6 16. Rd2 h4 17. h3 Ne5 18. Nc3 Be6 19. Rad1 Rfb8 20. Nd5 Bxd5 21. cxd5
Qd6 $11 {Mamedjarova,Z (2349)-Bologan,V (2669) Izmir 2004 (0-1, 66)}) 11. Nb1 {
Clearing the d2-square for the f3-knight and bringing the queen's knight
closer to d5.} (11. h3 e4 12. Nh2 Nc6 13. Qc2 Qe5 14. Rfd1 Re8 15. Nb1 Qg5 16.
Kh1 Ne5 17. Nc3 Bd7 18. Rd2 Bc6 19. Nd5 Bxd5 20. cxd5 c4 $11 {Heltzel,J (2115)
-Lalic,B (2540) Haarlem 2002 (0-1, 35)}) 11... Rd8 12. Qc2 e4 13. Nfd2 Nc6 14.
Nc3 Bf5 15. Rfd1 b6 16. Nf1 Bg6 $11 {Black controls more space and has little
to fear, Raisa,U (2260)-King,D (2545) Espoo 1991 (0-1, 59)}) 7... e5 8. d5 {
White once again faces problems maintaining the central tension.} (8. Bd3 O-O (
8... c5 {is also entirely playable.} 9. d5 Nh5 10. g3 O-O $11 {This is a
typical plan with the knight on d2, as White cannot afford to exchange on e5.
Black's knight would get to d4 while White's knight would still be far away
from d5.}) 9. O-O Bg4 10. h3 (10. Qc2 c5 $5 $146 11. d5 g6 12. Rfb1 Nh5 13. b4
Bxf3 14. Nxf3 Nd7 15. g3 Ng7 16. Nh4 b6 $11) 10... Bxf3 11. Nxf3 c5 12. d5 Nh5
13. g3 g6 14. Nh2 Nd7 15. b4 Ng7 16. Qd2 f5 $11 {Black is stable on the
queenside and has certain play on the kingside.} 17. f3 $2 Nh5 18. Kg2 f4 19.
g4 Ng3 20. Rfe1 h5 {, with excellent attacking chances in Lochte,T (2225)
-Dietz,H (2260) Wuerzburg 1995 (1/2-1/2, 57)}) (8. dxe5 dxe5 {offers Black
comfortable play. White does not even have the idea of Nd5 now.} 9. Be2 O-O 10.
O-O c5 11. b4 Nc6 12. Rb1 Rd8 13. Qb3 Bg4 $17 14. h3 $2 {Papadopoulou,V (2227)
-Foisor,C (2436) Athens 2004 (0-1, 38)} Rxd2 $19) 8... O-O 9. Be2 (9. Bd3 a5
10. b3 (10. O-O a4 {safely blocks the queenside, as White is not in time to
attack the pawn on a4 properly:} 11. Bc2 Bd7 $11 12. Nb1 $146 Na6 13. Nc3 Nc5
14. Ne1 c6 15. f3 cxd5 16. cxd5 Rfc8 17. Nd3 b5 $11) (10. b4 Nh5 11. g3 Na6 12.
O-O $2 Bh3 $17 {, with a double-attack on f1 and b4.}) 10... Nh5 11. g3 Na6 12.
Nh4 g6 (12... Nf4 $5) 13. Ng2 Bh3 14. Ne3 Nc5 15. Bc2 f5 {Black has the
initiative and the next tactical attempt will backfire:} 16. Nxf5 Qf6 17. Qe2
gxf5 18. Qxh5 Bg2 19. Rg1 Bxe4 $17 {Berkvens,J (2428)-Rogers,I (2547) Wijk aan
Zee 2002 (0-1, 47)}) 9... a5 10. b4 (10. O-O a4 11. Ne1 Bd7 $146 12. Nd3 Na6
$11) 10... Nh5 {The fastest way to achieve counterplay.} 11. g3 (11. Nxe5 $2
Nf4 $19) (11. O-O Nf4 12. Re1 f5 {, with the initiative in Sutherland,J (2030)
-Garbett,P (2313) Dunedin 2007 (0-1, 34)}) 11... Bh3 12. Bf1 (12. Nxe5 $2 {
still does not work:} Qxe5 13. Bxh5 axb4 $19) 12... Bd7 (12... Bxf1 13. Kxf1
Nd7 14. Kg2 f5 {is also good for Black.}) 13. Bg2 Na6 14. Rb1 Nf6 15. O-O {
It is interesting to compare this position to the similar one in Line 9. In
the current line, Black has spent two tempi on ...Nh5-f6 (instead of ...Nc6-b8
as in the other case), but he is basically a tempo up, as he has wasted only
one tempo with his bishop while White has lost two.} c6 16. Re1 (16. Qb3 axb4
17. axb4 cxd5 $5 $146 {Aiming for counterplay.} (17... c5 18. b5 Nb4 $11 {
, as played on a couple of occasions, is safe enough.}) 18. cxd5 (18. exd5 b5
19. Rfe1 bxc4 20. Nxc4 Rab8 21. Qa3 Bb5 22. Nfd2 Nc7 23. Ne3 Nfe8 24. Ra1 f5
$11) 18... Rfc8 {, with the usual queenside counterplay like in Line 12.})
16... axb4 17. axb4 c5 $146 (17... b5 $5 $146 {is more ambitious but also
double-edged.}) 18. b5 Nb4 $11 {Black has perfect stability on the dark
squares.} *

