1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. g3 Nc6 6. a3 {The idea behind
this move is familiar to us already. White simply intends to reach the optimal
development with the knight on c3. But as usual, Black can make use of the
extra tempo and sometimes of the weakness on b3.} (6. e3 {is examined in line
6.}) (6. Bg2 {is the second most popular move and will be examined in lines
7-12.}) (6. Nc3 {is the main move examined in lines 13-18.}) 6... Bxd2+ 7. Qxd2
(7. Nbxd2 {is less consistent but could transpose to lines 7-12, even though
a2-a3 does not make sense at such an early stage.} d6 8. Bg2 e5 9. d5 Nb8) 7...
d6 8. Bg2 ({The early attempt to take over the initiative with} 8. Nc3 e5 9.
Nd5 {can be met with} Nxd5 10. cxd5 e4 11. Ng5 {Nowak,M (2036)-Wozniak,M (2144)
Koszalin 2009 (1-0, 45)} (11. Nh4 {is the start of a seemingly more flexible
regrouping, which does not bother Black, though:} Nd8 12. Ng2 O-O 13. Ne3 f5 {
, with chances to take over the initiative on the kingside.}) (11. dxc6 exf3
$11 {reveals the importance of the tempo wasted on a2-a3. With the bishop on
g2 this would not work.}) 11... Nd8 $146 12. Bg2 f5 13. Nh3 c6 $5 14. dxc6 bxc6
15. Nf4 O-O 16. Rc1 a5 $11 {Black has good control over all the important
board sectors.}) 8... e5 9. Nc3 {White tries to maintain the tension in the
centre for as long as possible.} (9. d5 {is examined in Line 5.}) 9... Bg4 {
Forcing White to take a decision.} 10. dxe5 (10. d5 {allows} Bxf3 11. exf3 $5
Nd4 12. Rd1 $5 $146 ({More active than} 12. Qd1 O-O 13. O-O c5 14. dxc6 {
Hetey, L (2347)-Schebler,G (2485) Oberhausen 2010 (1-0, 39)} bxc6 15. f4 Rfe8
16. Re1 Rad8 17. b4 Qc7 $11) 12... c5 13. dxc6 bxc6 14. O-O O-O 15. f4 Rad8 16.
Rfe1 Qc7 17. b4 Rfe8 $11 {Black has harmonious development and good stability
on the dark squares .}) 10... dxe5 11. O-O (11. Nd5 {is premature yet:} Nxd5
12. cxd5 Bxf3 13. exf3 Nd4 14. Qd3 O-O-O ({More ambitious than} 14... O-O 15.
O-O c5 16. dxc6 Nxc6 $11) 15. O-O Rxd5 16. f4 Rb5 {An excellent square for the
rook, defending e5 and attacking b3 and b2.} 17. Rae1 Rd8 18. Qxh7 f5 {, with
interesting play and mutual chances.}) 11... O-O 12. Rad1 (12. Qe3 Qe6 $146 {
causes White some queenside problems.}) (12. Nd5 {may transpose to the
mainline.} Nxd5 13. cxd5 Rad8 (13... Bxf3 {looks a bit premature:} 14. exf3 Qd6
15. Rad1 Nd4 16. f4 f6 17. Rfe1 Rae8 {Black is hanging a bit but managed to
maintain his stability in the following game:} 18. Qc3 Kh8 19. Kh1 Qd7 20. fxe5
fxe5 21. Rc1 Nb5 22. Qd2 Re7 {1/2-1/2 Hehir,M (2252)-Anreiter,A (2205) ICCF
email 2017}) 14. Rfd1 (14. Rad1 {transposes to the mainline.}) 14... Bxf3 $1 {
The point is that the knight will gain a tempo by threatening ...Nb3.} 15. Bxf3
Nd4 $11 16. Qc3 $2 {Kleschtschow,J (2120) -Gustafsson,J (2340) Berlin 1996 
(0-1, 44)} Rxd5 $1 $17) 12... Rad8 13. Nd5 ({If} 13. Qe3 {, Black should keep
developing:} Rfe8 14. Ng5 (14. Nd5 {is less effective, as Qe3 mainly counts as
a waste of time.} Nxd5 15. cxd5 Bxf3 16. Qxf3 Nd4 17. Qd3 g6 18. e3 Nf5 $11 {
followed by ...Nd6 and ...f7-f5.}) (14. h3 Bxf3 15. Qxf3 Rd4 16. Rxd4 exd4 17.
Nd5 Qxe2 18. Nxf6+ gxf6 19. Qxf6 Ne5 $11 {Due to the strong passed pawn
sustained by the well-coordinated pieces, White does not have more than a
perpetual check.}) 14... Nd4 15. h3 Bh5 16. Nge4 Nxe4 17. Bxe4 c6 (17... f5 18.
Bd5+ Kh8 19. f4 c6 {is also good.}) 18. g4 Bg6 19. Bxg6 hxg6 20. Kg2 Qc5 21.
Qd3 Ne6 {Black has reached an optimal regrouping and his knight is better
placed than White's.} 22. Qe3 Rd4 $17 {Feng,R (2204)-Sang, T (2213) Redmond
2012 (1/2-1/2, 83)}) 13... Nxd5 14. cxd5 e4 $1 ({A more clear-cut solution to
the concrete problems than} 14... Bxf3 15. exf3 Nd4 16. f4 {, with a familiar
scenario.}) 15. Ng5 (15. Qf4 exf3 16. exf3 Bd7 17. Rfe1 Qd6 18. Qxd6 cxd6 19.
dxc6 Bxc6 20. f4 d5 $11) 15... e3 16. Qxe3 Qxe3 17. fxe3 Bxe2 18. dxc6 Bxd1 19.
cxb7 Be2 20. Rc1 Ba6 {White has compensation for the exchange but no more than
that.} 21. Rxc7 (21. b4 $2 h6 22. Nh3 c6 $1 23. Bxc6 Rb8 $17 {eliminates the
advanced pawn.}) 21... Rd1+ 22. Kf2 Rd2+ 23. Kg1 $11 {, with a draw by
perpetual.} (23. Kf3 Rxb2 $19 {wins the pawn on b7.}) *

