1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. g3 Nc6 6. a3 Bxd2+ 7. Qxd2 d6 8.
Bg2 e5 9. d5 {This is aimed to be an improved version of the Lines 7-12, as
the knight will develop more actively on c3.} Nb8 10. Nc3 ({Hurrying with} 10.
b4 {offers Black early counterplay:} a5 11. Qb2 (11. bxa5 {ensures Black's
queenside stability:} Na6 12. O-O O-O 13. Ne1 Nc5 14. Qb4 Bf5 {, with
excellent play.}) 11... e4 $5 12. Nd4 Nbd7 13. O-O Nb6 14. Rc1 e3 15. f4 O-O {
, with excellent black counterplay. White faces some problems with his
queenside development.}) 10... a5 11. O-O {Preventing ...a5-a4 wastes time.} (
11. Qc2 O-O 12. O-O Na6 13. Rab1 Nh5 14. b4 f5 {, with kingside counterplay.})
(11. b3 O-O 12. O-O Na6 13. b4 Nd7 14. Rfc1 ({If} 14. e4 {, trying to slow
down the kingside play, then} axb4 15. axb4 Nb6 $1 {, and suddenly the
queenside is hanging.}) 14... f5 15. c5 Nf6 $11) 11... a4 {Black has reached a
favourable queenside configuration, but should now hurry to complete his
development.} 12. Qc2 (12. c5 {fails to shake Black's stability and even
offers him a tempo for free.} Nbd7 13. cxd6 cxd6 14. Qc2 Nc5 15. Nd2 O-O 16. b4
axb3 17. Nxb3 Nfd7 18. Nd2 {Ton That Nhu,T (2206)-Nguyen,V (2425) Ho Chi Minh
City 2013 (1-0, 38)} b6 19. Nb5 Ba6 20. a4 f5 21. Nc4 Bxb5 22. axb5 e4 $5 $11 {
, with a stable position and active play.}) 12... Bd7 13. e4 (13. b4 {is an
interesting attempt to take over the initiative.} axb3 14. Qxb3 b6 15. c5 {
The only logical continuation, as otherwise ...Na6 would consolidate the
queenside.} Na6 (15... bxc5 $2 16. Qb7) (15... dxc5 16. Nd2 {offers White a
certain initiative for the pawn.}) 16. cxb6 Nc5 17. Qc2 ({Pawn grabbing is
time consuming:} 17. Qb2 cxb6 18. Qxb6 O-O 19. Qb2 e4 20. Nd4 Qe5 {Attacking
d5.} 21. Nc6 Bxc6 22. dxc6 Rfc8 {With the white bishop passive, Black does not
have problems at all.}) 17... cxb6 18. Rfb1 O-O $146 {Black should be aiming
for optimal regrouping based on ...Rfc8 or ...Rfb8.} (18... Rc8 19. Qd1 Rb8 {
yielded White a certain initiative:} 20. Nd2 O-O 21. Nc4 b5 22. Na5 $14 {
Ferrara,A (2261)-Benigni,D (2128) Buenos Aires 2001 (1/2-1/2, 46)}) 19. Rxb6 e4
20. Nd4 (20. Nd2 $2 e3 $15) 20... Qe5 21. Nc6 (21. Qd2 Nxd5 22. Nxd5 Qxd5 $11)
21... Bxc6 22. dxc6 Na4 {Black's initiative ensures the pawn's retrieval.} 23.
Rb3 Rac8 24. Rab1 Rxc6 25. Rb5 Rxc3 26. Qxa4 d5 27. Qb4 h5 28. a4 Rc2 {Black's
initiative and centralisation compensate for the outside passed pawn.}) 13...
O-O 14. Rae1 {Preparing a kingside attack based on f2-f4.} (14. Ne1 {fails to
question Black's stability on c5.} Ra5 $1 {Preparing not only ...Na6, but also
...Rc5 at a later stage.} (14... Qe8 {is more passive, but solid enough.} 15.
Nd3 Na6 16. f4 b6 {Antonsen,M (2400)-Dew,B (2094) Helsingor 2019 (1-0, 42)})
15. Nd3 Na6 16. Rae1 Ra8 17. f4 Nc5 18. Nb4 Nb3 19. f5 {Hassenrueck,H (2204)
-Thieme,H (2124) Bad Sooden 2014 (1/2-1/2, 42)} c5 $1 $146 20. dxc6 (20. Nd3 b5
$17) 20... bxc6 $15 {White experiences serious structural problems, without
having any clear attacking chances on the kingside.}) 14... Ra5 15. Re2 Na6 16.
Ne1 Nc5 17. f4 Nb3 18. Re3 Ng4 (18... Rc5 $5 {would cause White serious
problems regarding his coordination.} 19. Qd3 Ng4 20. Ref3 Nd4 {wins an
exchange.}) 19. Rd3 Nc5 20. Rdf3 {Weinberger,T (2240)-Orlov,G (2495) Las Vegas
1993 (0-1, 35)} exf4 21. gxf4 f5 $15 {White has structural problems on both
wings.} *

