1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. g3 Nc6 6. e3 {A solid move,
defending the d4 and c4 pawns in anticipation of ...Bxd2+, ...Qxd2 and ...Ne4.
But at the same time White weakens his light squares and wastes a developing
tempo.} O-O 7. Bg2 Bxd2+ 8. Qxd2 (8. Nfxd2 {is less popular. Its main drawback
is that it weakens the defence of d4.} d6 9. Nc3 e5 10. d5 (10. Nd5 Qd8 $11)
10... Nb8 11. O-O a5 12. a3 {Parligras,M (2645)-Tomici,S (2316) Bucharest 2018
(1-0, 65)} Bf5 $1 $146 {Provoking the next move.} 13. e4 Bd7 14. b4 Na6 15. Qb3
Rfb8 {, followed by ...c7-c6, with play similar to some lines below.}) 8... d6
(8... d5 9. O-O dxc4 {, followed by ...e6-e5, is a popular alternative, but I
prefer sticking to our main pattern.}) 9. Nc3 e5 10. Nd5 {This is part of
White's plan, but played at this stage it offers Black a choice.} (10. O-O {
can also be met in different ways, actually.} Bg4 ({Black can invite a
transposition with} 10... Re8 11. Nd5 Qd8) 11. h3 {Melkumyan,H (2534)-Bachmann,
A (2519) ICC INT 2008 (1/2-1/2, 46)} (11. Nd5 Nxd5 12. cxd5 e4 {Now the
weakness on f3 makes itself felt.} 13. Nh4 Nd8 14. f3 exf3 15. Nxf3 Re8 16.
Rae1 f6 {, with a flexible position.}) (11. Rae1 Rae8 $5 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Bxf3
e4 14. Bg2 Nb8 15. f3 exf3 16. Bxf3 c6 17. e4 Nbd7 {White's position looks
impressive, but Black can prepare ...c6-c5 (possibly with ...Qd8-a5) in order
to take control over the dark squares.}) 11... Bxf3 12. Bxf3 exd4 13. exd4 Qe6
$1 {, forcing mass simplifications.} 14. Nd5 (14. d5 Ne5 $1 {, with active
play.}) 14... Nxd5 15. cxd5 Qf6 16. dxc6 Qxf3 17. cxb7 Qxb7 $11) 10... Qd8 (
10... Nxd5 11. cxd5 Nd8 {is an important alternative. In view of the next
exchange, the knight is heading for d6.} 12. dxe5 (12. O-O e4 13. Ne1 Bf5 14.
Rc1 c6 $11) (12. e4 f5 {, with counterplay. In this line e2-e3 clearly looks
like a waste of time.}) 12... dxe5 13. O-O f6 14. Rac1 (14. Ne1 {, aiming to
meet ...c7-c6xd5 with Nb4, can be met with} Nf7 15. Rc1 Nd6 16. e4 f5 {, with
adequate counterplay.}) 14... c6 15. e4 (15. d6 Qd7 16. Rfd1 Nf7 {causes White
problems with the far advanced pawn.} 17. Ne1 $6 Rd8 18. Rc3 Qe8 19. Rd3 Bg4
20. f3 e4 $15) 15... cxd5 16. exd5 Nf7 $11 {, followed by ...Nd6, with
comfortable play.}) 11. O-O Re8 12. Qc3 $5 {The most constructive move,
clearing the d2-square for the knight in view of the threat ...e5-e4 and
keeping d4 defended.} (12. Qc2 exd4 13. exd4 (13. Nxd4 Nxd4 14. exd4 c6 15. Ne3
Be6 $11) 13... Nxd5 14. cxd5 Ne7 $11) (12. Rad1 e4 13. Ne1 Nxd5 14. cxd5 Nb8
15. Qc2 Bf5 16. f3 Qe7 $11 17. g4 $6 Bg6 18. f4 f5 $15 {White's minor pieces
are passive and the pawn on d5 could become weak.}) (12. Rac1 {anticipates the
course of events in the line above by indirectly putting pressure on c7. But
it does not threaten much and Black can simply strengthen his position with,
say,} a5 {Preparing ...Nb4 in a similar line as above.}) 12... Ne4 (12... e4
13. Nxf6+ Qxf6 14. Nd2 Bf5 15. f3 $14) (12... Bg4 $5) 13. Qc2 exd4 14. exd4 (
14. Nxd4 Nxd4 15. exd4 Bf5 {can lead to interesting play:} 16. Rfe1 c6 $11 17.
Ne3 (17. Bxe4 Rxe4 18. Rxe4 cxd5 19. cxd5 Qa5 20. Qe2 Bxe4 21. Qxe4 g6 $11)
17... Bg6 18. f4 Nxg3 19. f5 Rxe3 20. fxg6 Rxe1+ 21. Rxe1 Nh5 22. gxf7+ Kxf7
23. Qxh7 Nf6 24. Rf1 Qa5 $11) 14... Bg4 15. Rad1 Nf6 16. h3 (16. Ng5 {leads to
interesting complications, too:} Bxd1 17. Nxf6+ Qxf6 18. Qxh7+ Kf8 19. Qh8+ Ke7
20. Re1+ Ne5 21. Qh4 Qh6 22. Qf4 Bh5 23. Bxb7 Rab8 24. dxe5 Kf8 $11 {White has
compensation for the exchange but not more.}) 16... Bxf3 17. Bxf3 Nxd5 18. cxd5
Qf6 19. Qc3 Ne7 20. Rfe1 g6 21. Re4 Nf5 22. Rf4 Qd8 $11 {At this height Black
does not have any special problems, Eljanov,P (2719) -Ivanchuk,V (2726) Lvov
2014 (1-0, 66)} *

