Bg2 {As disappointing as it may be for White, this most desirable move has a
major drawback.} Bxd2+ 7. Qxd2 Ne4 8. Qc2 Qb4+ 9. Nbd2 (9. Kf1 {causes a major
waste of time, offering Black easy play.} f5 10. a3 Qe7 11. b4 O-O 12. Nc3 Nxc3
13. Qxc3 d6 14. e3 Nd8 ({I slightly prefer this flexible regrouping over} 14...
e5 {, which is entirely playable, too.} 15. b5 exd4 16. Nxd4 Ne5 17. h3 Kh8 18.
Kg1 Nd7 19. Kh2 Nc5 {, with comfortable stability on the dark squares.
Mamedyarov,S (2817)-Rapport,R (2731) Wijk aan Zee 2019 (1/2-1/2, 40)}) 15. Ke2
Nf7 16. Rhd1 e5 $11 {Weber,K (2364)-Kurpnieks,V (2173) ICCF email 2015 (1/2-1/
2, 44)}) (9. Nc3 Nxc3 {spoils White's structure without even yielding him the
two bishops as in the Nimzo-Indian.} 10. Qxc3 (10. bxc3 Qxc4 {wins a pawn
without real compensation.}) 10... Qxc3+ 11. bxc3 Na5 12. Nd2 Rb8 13. c5 {
A thematic but strategically risky move.} (13. O-O {is more cautious.} b6 14.
Rfb1 Ke7 15. Rb4 d6 16. Nb3 Bd7 17. Nxa5 bxa5 18. Rb3 a4 19. Rbb1 e5 20. Be4 f5
21. Bc2 c5) 13... b6 14. Nb3 Ba6 15. Bf3 ({If} 15. Nxa5 bxa5 $15 {White cannot
