1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. g3 Nc6 6. Bg2 Bxd2+ 7. Nbxd2 d6 8.
Nf1 $5 {An interesting way of activating the knight at an early stage. On e3
it will control several important squares, but it will also block the e-pawn.}
(8. O-O O-O 9. e4 {is examined in the next lines.}) (8. e4 e5 {mainly
transposes to later lines, too.}) 8... O-O 9. Ne3 e5 10. O-O Re8 {At this
height, both sides play a half-waiting game. The last move makes the threat ...
e5-e4 real.} ({The point is that} 10... e4 $6 11. Nd2 Nxd4 {Otherwise the
knight on e3 would have a wonderful blocking position.} 12. Nxe4 $14 Nxe2+ $2 {
loses to} 13. Qxe2 Nxe4 14. Nd5 {, and the knight on e4 is lost.}) 11. Re1 {
Parrying the threat by indirect means.} ({If} 11. dxe5 dxe5 12. Nd5 {The calm
retreat} Qd8 {maintains Black's stability. He can now answer neutral moves
with either ...e5-e4 or ...Be6.} 13. Ne1 $5 {The reserve knight is heading for
e3.} Nd4 (13... Bf5 14. Nc2 Bg6 {is also comfortable for Black.}) 14. Nc2 (14.
e3 Ne6 {may transpose.}) 14... c6 15. Nxf6+ Qxf6 16. e3 {White cannot tolerate
the central knight anymore, but the last move puts an end to the plan based on
Ne3.} Ne6 {At this height it is obvious that Black is better regrouped.} 17. b4
{Preventing ...a7-a5 followed by ...Nc5, but the black knight has other
perspectives, too. In Serrano,E-Hernandez Onna,R (2430) Collado Villalba 1997 
(0-1, 34) he could have gone to the other wing:} Ng5 18. f4 exf4 19. exf4 Nh3+
20. Kh1 Bf5 $15) (11. d5 {is not very effective with the knight blocking the
e2-pawn.} Nb8 12. b4 a5 13. a3 Ng4 14. Qb3 Nxe3 15. Qxe3 Nd7 16. Rac1 b6 17.
Rc2 Nf6 (17... f5 $5) 18. Nd2 Bf5 19. Ne4 (19. Rcc1 e4 20. Nb3 axb4 21. axb4
Qe5 22. Nd4 Bd7 23. Ra1 h5 $15) 19... axb4 20. axb4 Bxe4 21. Bxe4 {At this
height Black's position is more pleasant already, as the white bishop is not
worth very much.} Qd7 (21... h5) (21... Ra4) 22. Bg2 Ra4 23. Rb1 Rea8 24. h3 h5
25. c5 (25. Qg5 e4 26. c5 Ra2 $15 {keeps White's counterplay under control.})
25... Qf5 $15 {Graf,F (2262)-Kuzubov,Y (2545) Dresden 2007 (0-1, 34)}) (11. Rc1
{allows} e4 $5 12. Nd2 (12. Ng5 h6 13. Nh3 Qd8 14. Nf4 Ne7 $11 {, planning ...
c7-c6, for instance} 15. Qc2 c6 16. Bxe4 Nxe4 17. Qxe4 Nf5 18. Qd3 Nxe3 19.
fxe3 Qe7 20. Rc3 Bd7 {White's extra pawn is not too relevant and his king is a
bit weak.}) 12... Nxd4 13. Nxe4 Nxe2+ 14. Qxe2 Nxe4 15. Nd5 Qd8 16. Rfe1 (16.
Bxe4 f5) 16... c6 (16... Bd7 $5 17. Bxe4 f5 18. Qd3 fxe4 19. Rxe4 Rxe4 20. Qxe4
Qg5 $11) 17. Bxe4 f5 18. Nf6+ gxf6 19. Bd5+ Kf8 20. Qxe8+ Qxe8 21. Rxe8+ Kxe8
22. Re1+ Kf8 23. Be6 d5 24. cxd5 Bxe6 25. Rxe6 Kf7 $1 26. Rd6 Ke7 27. Re6+ Kf7
$11 {drawn.}) (11. Nd5 $5 $146 Nxd5 12. cxd5 Nxd4 13. Nxd4 exd4 14. Bf3 Qe5 15.
Rc1 Bf5 16. Rxc7 d3 $11 {Attacking b2, with enough play for the pawn.}) 11...
