1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. g3 Nc6 6. Bg2 Bxd2+ 7. Nbxd2 d6 8.
O-O O-O 9. e4 e5 10. d5 Nb8 11. Ne1 {The start of a harmonious regrouping.} a5
12. Nd3 {The White knights' display looks aesthetically pleasing. They can
sustain an attack on either wing.} (12. f4 exf4 13. gxf4 Na6 14. Nd3 {
transposes.}) 12... Na6 {In the meantime Black sticks to his general plan.} 13.
Qc2 {White tries to prepare his pawn attack in the best way. His target is the
pawn on a5.} (13. b3 c6 $11) (13. Qe2 {is not that constructive at this stage.}
Bd7 14. f4 Nb4 15. Nxb4 axb4 16. f5 {1/2-1/2 Gross,S (2435)-Hracek,Z (2485)
Rimavska Sobota 1991. Black has good counterplay along the a-file while
White's attack is not easy to carry out:} Ra4 17. b3 (17. g4 h6 18. h4 Rfa8 $17
{is similar.}) 17... Ra5 18. g4 h6 19. h4 Rfa8 (19... Nh7 20. Nf3 c5 21. Rf2 b5
$15 {is also good, but Black does not need to fear g4-g5.}) 20. g5 hxg5 21.
hxg5 Nh7 $17 22. f6 (22. g6 fxg6 23. fxg6 Nf6 $17 24. Nf3 $2 {The only way to
defend the pawn, creating even worse problems.} Nh5 $19 {, followed by ...Nf4.}
) 22... gxf6 23. gxf6 Nxf6 24. Rf3 Rxa2 25. Raf1 Ng4 26. Rxf7 Qh4 $19) (13. a3
{[%emt 0:00:11] is examined in line}) (13. f4 {is line 12.}) 13... Bd7 (13...
c6 {is a bit premature due to} 14. Qc3 (14. dxc6 bxc6 15. c5 Nxc5 16. Nxc5 dxc5
17. Rfc1 {offered White just a symbolic advantage in So,W (2646)-Kuzubov,Y 
(2635) Lubbock 2009 (1/2-1/2, 35)}) 14... cxd5 15. cxd5 Bd7 16. a4 $1 (16. Qxa5
Nc5 17. Qc3 Bb5 18. Nxc5 Bxf1 19. Bxf1 Rfc8) (16. Rfc1 Rfc8 $11 17. Qxa5 $2 Nc5
18. Qc3 Ncxe4 $17) 16... Rfc8 17. Qb3 (17. Qa3 b5) 17... Be8 {Picart,L (2094)
-Rosenkilde,A (2235) Kaunas 2011 (1/2-1/2, 21)} 18. Rfc1 $14 {, with a certain
queenside pressure.}) 14. Qc3 ({Combining play on both sides, is double-edged.
} 14. Rae1 c6 15. Qc3 cxd5 16. cxd5 Rfc8 17. Qb3 Qd8 $11 18. f4 $2 a4 $17 {
[%cal Gd7b5,Gc8c2,Gd8b6] , followed by ...Qb6+, ...Bb5, and possibly ...Rc2.})
(14. f4 {is a bit premature.} Nb4 15. Qc3 Nxd3 16. Qxd3 exf4 $5 $146 17. gxf4
Nh5 {White starts experiencing some stability problems.} 18. Rae1 Rae8 19. e5
Qh4 20. Qf3 b6 21. Re3 Re7 $11 {Black has no problems at all, as he has found
good squares for all his pieces. It is White who should be careful, if he does
not wish to simplify with exd6.} 22. b3 Rfe8 23. Kh1 $2 dxe5 24. fxe5 Bg4 $17 {
Suddenly there are no good squares for the queen along the f-file, and White
wins the pawn on e5.}) 14... b6 {With the pawn still on c7, this is more of a
consolidating than a weakening move.} 15. f4 (15. b3 {Iljushin,A (2410)
-Lomineishvili,M (2385) Moscow 1997 (1-0, 52)} Rac8 $5 16. f4 exf4 17. gxf4 c6
18. e5 Ng4 {, and White starts to be hanging.}) (15. Rae1 Nb4 $11) 15... Rfe8
16. Rae1 (16. f5 c6 17. dxc6 Bxc6 18. Nf2 b5 {offers Black quick counterplay
while the kingside attack is still slow.}) 16... Nb4 {The typical knight jump,
dismantling White's perfect attacking setup.} 17. Nc1 (17. Nxb4 axb4 18. Qxb4
Rxa2 $11) 17... c6 18. a3 Na6 19. Nd3 Nc5 20. Nxc5 bxc5 21. Nf3 {Sardo,G (2229)
-Sanchez Enriquez,O (2383) Amantea 2014 (1/2-1/2, 69)} (21. f5 a4 22. Bf3 Reb8
23. g4 h6 $15 {puts White's attack into a dead end while Black's queenside
play is promising.} 24. h4 $2 Nh7 $17) 21... exf4 22. e5 dxe5 23. Nxe5 cxd5 24.
Bxd5 Nxd5 25. cxd5 Bh3 26. Rxf4 Qd6 $11 *

