1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. g3 Nc6 6. Bg2 Bxd2+ 7. Nbxd2 d6 8.
O-O O-O 9. e4 e5 10. d5 Nb8 11. Ne1 a5 12. Nd3 Na6 13. f4 {The kingside attack
leads to double-edged play after Black's principled answer.} exf4 ({Staying
passive when queenside counterplay has not even started yet is less promising.
} 13... Nd7 14. f5 f6 15. a3 Ndc5 16. Nxc5 Nxc5 17. b4 axb4 18. axb4 Rxa1 19.
Qxa1 Na6 20. Qa5 $14) (13... c6 14. Qb3 $14) 14. gxf4 Bg4 15. Qe1 (15. Bf3 {
This exchange weakens the king's defence and solves Black's space problems.}
Bxf3 16. Qxf3 Nd7 ({This is a good maneuvre, but not necessary at this stage.} 
16... Rae8 $5 {followed by ...Nb4 is also sufficient, as if} 17. e5 Nd7 18.
Rae1 Nb4 $15 {, White is hanging.}) 17. Rfe1 Nb4 18. Nxb4 axb4 19. Qg3 f5 $15 {
Megacal (2419)-Vmencin (2406) playchess.com INT 2006 (0-1, 48)} 20. e5 dxe5 21.
fxe5 f4) 15... Nb4 {Reducing the force of e4-e5.} 16. Nxb4 axb4 17. Qg3 Bd7 18.
e5 Nh5 {Despite White's space advantage, Black is doing fine here. The pawn on
a2 is hanging and the black pieces have good squares.} 19. Qe3 (19. Qf3 g6 $11)
19... Rfe8 20. Qf2 Bf5 21. Rfe1 g6 22. Nf1 $6 dxe5 $1 {The signal to the
counter-attack.} 23. fxe5 Qg5 24. Re3 Nf4 25. Qg3 Qh6 $15 {Black's minor
pieces are very active and the White centre may be hanging soon. Ponomarev,A 
(2459)-Teichmeister,S (2567) ICCF email 2008 (0-1, 53)} *

