1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. g3 Nc6 6. Bg2 Bxd2+ 7. Nbxd2 d6 8.
O-O O-O 9. e4 e5 10. d5 Nb8 11. Ne1 a5 12. Nd3 Na6 13. a3 {The queenside plan
is more solid, but it offers Black the possibility of organizing his
counterplay on the same side.} Bg4 $1 {An important intermediate move,
inducing the weakening of the g1-a7 diagonal.} 14. f3 {The only way to keep
White's play consistent.} (14. Qc2 Be2 15. Rfe1 Bxd3 16. Qxd3 Nc5 17. Qc3 a4 {
[%cal Gc7c6] Securing the queenside and planning ...c7-c6.} 18. f4 exf4 19.
gxf4 Nh5 20. Qe3 Qh4 21. Rf1 Rfe8 $11 {, with good counterplay.}) (14. Qe1 a4
$1 $146 {First things first.} (14... c6 15. f4 cxd5 16. cxd5 exf4 17. gxf4 Rae8
{Golod,V (2532)-Mindlin,A (2462) Israel 2019 (0-1, 61)} 18. Qf2 $14 {leaves
the knight passive on a6.}) 15. f4 exf4 16. gxf4 Nd7 $11 {, followed by ...
Nac5 and ...Rae8.}) 14... Bd7 15. b4 c6 $1 {This typical move, preparing to
open the queenside and clearing the a5-d8 diagonal for the queen, is best
played without the exchange on b4.} (15... axb4 16. axb4 {opens the a-file for
the a1-rook.} c6 17. dxc6 bxc6 18. Qc2 d5 ({This is the reaction examined in
the mainline, but} 18... h5 19. Qc3 h4 {may be the lesser evil. In either case,
the exposed position of the knight a6 becomes a problem.}) 19. Qc3 d4 20. Qb2
Rfb8 21. Ra5 $16) 16. dxc6 (16. bxa5 {is not dangerous. The pawn is likely to
be lost and Black gets play on the dark squares .} Qd8 17. Nb3 (17. dxc6 Bxc6
18. Nb3 Ba4 19. Qb1 Qc7 20. Rc1 b6 $1 21. Nd2 bxa5 22. Qb2 Nc5 $15 {Taher,Y 
(2469)-Bogdanovich, S (2562) Bhopal 2019 (0-1, 48)}) (17. f4 {1-0 (26) Hrubaru,
M (2009)-Pech,J (1257) FICGS email 2010} exf4 18. gxf4 cxd5 19. cxd5 Bb5 $11)
17... cxd5 18. cxd5 Ba4 19. Rb1 (19. Bh3 Nc7 20. Nb2 Rxa5 21. Rf2 Nb5 $11)
19... Bxb3 20. Qxb3 Qxa5 21. Qxb7 Qxa3 {White needs to think of maintaining
equality already. Pech,J-Kortig,S DESC email 2011 (1/2-1/2, 29)}) ({Keeping
the tension offers Black a clear regrouping plan.} 16. Qb3 cxd5 17. cxd5 axb4
18. axb4 Nc7 {Black's minor pieces can use the square b5 while White's
kingside is likely to be weak.} 19. Nc4 (19. Rfc1 Nb5 20. Qb2 {Laketic,G (2427)
-Vratonjic, S (2401) Kragujevac 2015 (1/2-1/2, 34)} Rxa1 21. Rxa1 h5 22. h4 Ne8
$15 {, followed by ...g7-g5.}) (19. Qb2 Bb5 20. Ra3 Rxa3 21. Qxa3 Ba6 22. Rc1
Nb5 23. Qa5 Nd4 24. Bf1 Nh5 $17 25. Nf2 {0-1 (35) Skembris,S (2525)-Beliavsky,
A (2650) Igalo 1994} Bxf1 26. Kxf1 Qg5 27. Rd1 f5 $19) 19... Nb5 20. Qb2 Rxa1
21. Rxa1 Ne8 (21... Rc8 22. Nb6 Rc3 23. Bf1 Be8 24. Na4 Rc7 25. Nb6 Nd4 26. Ne1
Nd7 27. Nc4 b5 28. Ne3 Nb6 29. Rc1 h5 {Sethuraman,S (2535)-Nguyen,V (2429)
Kuala Lumpur 2010 (0-1, 74)}) (21... h5 $5) 22. Na5 (22. f4 f6 $11) 22... Nd4
23. Nc1 f5 24. Ne2 {Gordon,S (2490)-Palac,M (2568) Dresden 2007 (1-0, 41)} Nb5
$11) 16... bxc6 17. Qc2 {The most natural move, keeping the knights defended
and preparing c4-c5..} (17. Qb3 {is a bit committal, exposing the queen along
the b-file. But I would just play} h5 $5 $146 {, taking advantage of the fact
that the white queen is far away from the kingside.}) (17. Qe2 Rfb8 (17... Rfe8
18. Rfe1 Rab8 {is another harmonious rooks' display.} 19. Rab1 axb4 20. axb4 d5
21. exd5 Nxb4 22. Qxe5 Qf8 23. Qd4 Rxe1+ 24. Nxe1 cxd5 25. cxd5 Nbxd5 $11) (
17... h5 $5 {remains a valid idea, too.}) 18. Rfb1 Nc7 $11 19. f4 $6 Ne6 (19...
exf4 $1 20. gxf4 d5 21. cxd5 cxd5 $15 {would leave White hanging.} 22. e5 $6
Bb5 $17 {, followed by ...Bxd3 and ...Nh5.}) 20. Nf3 exf4 21. gxf4 Nh5 22. Qd2
Qf6 $1 {The best way to start the counterattack without opening the a-file.} (
22... axb4 23. axb4 Rxa1 24. Rxa1 Qf6 25. Ra7 $14 {Soln,P (2235)-Loginov,V 
(2610) Vienna 1994 (1/2-1/2, 55)}) 23. f5 Nd4 24. Qf2 Nxf3+ 25. Bxf3 Qg5+ 26.
Kh1 Nf4 27. Qe3 Ne6 $11) (17. Nb3 {forces} axb4 18. axb4 {, but allows the
central break} d5 $1 {Due to possible checks on the weak diagonal, White is
hanging.} 19. c5 (19. Nbc5 Nxb4 $1 20. Rxa8 Rxa8 21. Nxd7 Nxd7 22. cxd5 Nxd3
23. Qxd3 Qc5+ 24. Kh1 Ra3 25. Qd2 cxd5 26. exd5 Ra4 27. Rc1 Rd4 28. Rxc5 Rxd2
29. Rc8+ Nf8 $15) (19. b5 Nb4 20. Rxa8 Rxa8 21. bxc6 dxc4 22. Nxb4 Qxb4 23.
cxd7 Qb6+ 24. Kh1 cxb3 $11) 19... dxe4 20. fxe4 Be6 21. Qc2 (21. Nxe5 Nxb4 $15)
21... Ng4 22. Na5 (22. Qc3 Qg5 23. Rfe1 Nc7 $15) 22... Ne3 $17 {Van der
Sterren,P (2515)-Douven,R (2475) Amsterdam 1989 (1/2-1/2, 49)}) 17... d5 (17...
h5 $5 $146 {remains an attractive idea. The plan is ...h5-h4 followed by ...Nh5
} 18. c5 $5 axb4 19. axb4 Be6 20. Qc3 dxc5 21. bxc5 Nd7 22. Rfc1 Nc7 $11 {
Black gets excellent compensation for the pawn(s) after} 23. Nxe5 Rxa1 24. Qxa1
Ra8 25. Qc3 Nxe5 26. Qxe5 Nb5 27. Nf1 (27. Qxh5 $2 Qd8 $1 28. Nf1 Qd4+ 29. Kh1
Ra2 $19) 27... Ra2 28. Ne3 Qd8 29. Rd1 Rd2 30. Rxd2 Qxd2 31. Nf1 Qd1 32. Qxh5
Nd4 $11 {Black's threats on the weakened kingside are enough to keep chances
even.}) 18. c5 ({With the a-file closed,} 18. Qc3 {is not dangerous.} d4 19.
Qb2 Rfb8 20. Rfb1 Be8) 18... dxe4 19. fxe4 Ng4 20. Nc4 {Rashkovsky,N (2535)
-Maharramzade,J (2440) Ubeda 1999 (1-0, 38)} axb4 $5 $146 21. h3 (21. Nb6 b3 $1
) (21. axb4 Nxb4 $1) 21... Nf6 22. Nb6 b3 23. Qxb3 Rad8 24. Qc4 Nc7 $11 {
Black is doing fine. He has the better structure and squares to play for. The
a-pawn is rather slow.} *

