1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. g3 Nc6 6. Nc3 {White anticipates
the threat ...Bxd2+ with a natural developing move. True, this exposes the
knight to a Nimzo-Indian scenario (...Bxc3), but only after Black has made a
few commitments (...Qe7, ...Nc6).} Bxc3 {Black prepares the knight invasion to
e4 with a possible second exchange on c3, thus re-entering the Bogo patterns,
with both dark-squared bishops off the board.} ({There were times when} 6...
O-O 7. Bg2 d5 {was fashionable, too, but our repertoire is based on displaying
our central pawns on the dark squares .}) 7. Bxc3 Ne4 8. Qc2 {White
immediately forces the knight to make a decision. But the early queen
development does not lead to the best placement of White's pieces.} (8. Rc1 {
is the subject of lines 15-18.}) 8... Nxc3 9. Qxc3 O-O 10. Bg2 d6 11. O-O {
A neutral continuation, allowing Black to carry out his main plan.} ({White
could make use of the queen's presence on c3 to start an early queenside
attack with} 11. b4 {, but this is likely to lead to simplification and a
drawn ending.} e5 12. b5 Nxd4 (12... Nb8 $5 {is interesting, but a bit on the
edge. Black plans ...Nd7, keeping some control over c5 and preparing for ...
e5-e4 and/or ...f7-f5.} 13. dxe5 Re8 14. O-O dxe5 15. c5 {Otherwise ...Nd7-c5.}
a6 16. a4 axb5 17. axb5 Rxa1 18. Rxa1 Bd7 {A provocative way of fighting
against White's space advantage.} 19. Qb4 e4 20. Nd4 c6 21. b6 Na6 22. Rxa6 $1
bxa6 23. e3 {I would enjoy playing this with White despite the missing
exchange. The b-pawn is very strong and White will soon have perfect
coordination after Bf1}) 13. Nxd4 exd4 14. Qxd4 Re8 15. e3 Qe5 16. Rd1 Rb8 17.
a4 a5 18. Bd5 b6 19. Qxe5 Rxe5 20. h3 Bd7 21. Kd2 Rbe8 $11 {Repanic,F (2159)
-Junge,W (2373) ICCF email 2017 (1/2-1/2, 33) For those who have a good memory,
I should clarify an important detail. Anand-Aronian, Candidates' tournament
Moscow 2016, has reached an almost identical ending. But there was a notable
difference. Black's rook was arrested on a7, so Black had to exchange on d5 at
some point, resulting in a considerable white advantage after cxd5. Anand
eventually won. But in the current position, Black does not have any special
problems.}) (11. d5 {is examined in Line 14.}) 11... e5 12. d5 {The most
principled move.} (12. dxe5 {fails to cause Black any real problems.} dxe5 13.
Rfd1 Bg4 (13... e4 $5) (13... f5 $5) 14. Rd2 Rad8 15. Rad1 {Adamek,J (2254)
-Kulhanek,T (2428) Ostrava 2010 (1/2-1/2, 33)} f6 16. h3 Be6 $11) (12. e3 {
is solid but not too challenging either.} a5 {Probably the most constructive
move at this stage, increasing control over the dark squares .} (12... Bg4 {
is good enough if Black wishes to more or less force a draw:} 13. h3 Bxf3 14.
Bxf3 Qf6 15. Bxc6 exd4 16. Qxd4 Qxd4 17. exd4 bxc6 18. Rfe1 Rfe8 19. Kf1 Kf8 {
В1/2-В1/2 Cvitan,O (2550)-Yrjola,J (2435) Pula 1997}) 13. Rad1 Bg4 (13... Re8
$5) (13... h6 $5) 14. h3 Bd7 $146 (14... Bh5 15. dxe5 dxe5 16. Rd5 {1/2-1/2
Cvitan,O (2560)-Wahls,M (2605) Dresden 1998} f6 17. Rb5 {causes certain
queenside problems.}) 15. Kh2 Rfe8) 12... Nb8 13. c5 {The most direct way of
starting the queenside attack. Other natural moves offer Black a free tempo.} (
13. e4 a5 14. c5 b6 {A reliable way of stabilising the queenside. Black
defends a5 in order to allow ...Na6.} (14... f5 {looks like a good alternative:
} 15. exf5 Bxf5 16. Rfe1 Nd7) (14... Nd7 {may be premature:} 15. cxd6 cxd6 16.
Rfc1 Re8 17. Nd2 b6 18. Qa3 Ba6 19. Rc6 Bb5 20. Rc7 Qg5 21. Nc4 Bxc4 22. Rxd7
$16 {Swiercz,D (2594)-Moiseenko,A (2706) Istanbul 2012 (1-0, 48)}) 15. cxb6 (
15. c6 {slows down the attack:} Na6 16. b3 f5 17. exf5 Bxf5 18. Nh4 Bg4 19.
Rae1 Nc5 20. a3 b5 {Black has a promising position on both wings.} 21. f4 $6 g5
$1 $15) 15... cxb6 16. Rfc1 Na6 {Securing the c-file.} 17. Nd2 Nc5 18. Qe3 (18.
Nc4 Rb8 19. Rc2 f5 {is also comfortable for Black.}) 18... f5 19. exf5 Bxf5 20.
f4 Rae8 21. fxe5 Nd3 22. Rc3 Nxe5 $15 {Kuhn,W (1941)-Walther,J (2003) GER
email 2013 (0-1, 50)} 23. Qxb6 $2 Nd3 $17) (13. b4 f5 14. c5 Nd7 15. cxd6 cxd6
16. Qc7 {Sarosi,Z (2320)-Berczes,C (2402) Hungary 2010 (0-1, 27)} Qf6 $5 $146
17. Nd2 Rf7 $11 18. Nc4 $2 Nb6 $19) 13... Nd7 (13... b6 $2 {does not work
without ... a7-a5 as the rook is vulnerable to} 14. cxd6 cxd6 15. Nxe5 $1 $16)
14. cxd6 {White's only constructive plan is to open the c-file.} (14. b4 {
does not bring in anything positive.} e4 15. Nd2 (15. cxd6 cxd6 16. Nd4 Nf6 $11
) 15... f5 $11) 14... cxd6 15. Rfc1 ({Another possible move order is} 15. Qc7
Re8 16. Nd2 Nf6 17. Qxe7 Rxe7 18. e4 Bd7 19. Rac1 Kf8 20. Nc4 Bb5 21. Rfd1 {
Pilgram,K (1816) -Rivas Romero,J (1434) LSS email 2013 (1/2-1/2, 49)} Bxc4 22.
Rxc4 Nd7 23. Rdc1 a5 24. Rc8+ Rxc8 25. Rxc8+ Re8 26. Rc7 Nc5 $11) 15... f5 16.
Nd2 Nf6 17. Nc4 e4 18. Qa5 g6 $5 $146 {A useful move, over-defending f5.} (
18... Bd7 {is premature:} 19. Qc7 Nxd5 (19... Rab8 {runs into} 20. Qxd6 Qxd6
21. Nxd6 Nxd5 22. Bh3 $1 {, when the threat Nxe4 is hard to meet.} e3 23. f4
$14) 20. Qxb7 $14 {, with a certain white initiative in Wilczek,T (2667)-Cleto,
F (2496) ICCF email 2010 (1/2-1/2, 39)}) 19. Rc2 (19. e3 {allows a similar
reaction.} Bd7 20. Qc7 Rab8 21. Qxd6 Qxd6 22. Nxd6 Nxd5 23. Bh3 Bc6 $11 {
As the f5-pawn is defended, Black can parry Nxe4 with a consolidating move.})
19... Bd7 20. Qc7 Rab8 21. Qxd6 (21. Rd1 Rfc8 $1 {leaves the knight pinned.})
21... Qxd6 22. Nxd6 Nxd5 23. Bh3 Bc6 {, with at least equal play for Black.} *

