1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. g3 Nc6 6. Nc3 Bxc3 7. Bxc3 Ne4 8.
Qc2 Nxc3 9. Qxc3 O-O 10. Bg2 d6 11. d5 $5 {A typical attempt at crossing
Black's main plan.} Nd8 {This retreat ensures Black the most fluent play.} (
11... Nb8 {, hoping to transpose to the previous line with ...e6-e5, is
answered with} 12. dxe6 fxe6 {This is a popular tabyia, but I do not like
Black's structure so much.}) 12. O-O (12. dxe6 Nxe6 {justifies the knight
retreat to d8.} 13. O-O Bd7 14. Rfe1 ({Against} 14. e4 {I recommend the same
plan as below:} c5 $5 $146) 14... Rfe8 ({The usual plan in this structure is} 
14... Bc6 15. e4 a5 {, ensuring Black stability on the dark squares. But in
principle White retains more active play with, say,} 16. Nh4 $14 {Kaidanov,G 
(2599)-Leitao,R (2565) New York 2000 (1/2-1/2, 31)}) 15. e4 (15. Rad1 $5 $146
Rad8 {continues the half-waiting game.} 16. Nd4 Nxd4 17. Qxd4 b6 18. b4 Qe5 19.
e3 a6 20. a3 h5 $11) 15... c5 $5 $146 {With the d4-square weak and the enemy
knight far from d5, this looks like the most reliable setup. The plan with Nh4
runs into ...Nd4 and otherwise Black can play ...Bc6 followed by ... a7-a6 and
...b6-b5.} 16. Rad1 Rad8 17. b4 a6 18. a3 Bc6 $11 {, possibly followed by ...
b7-b5.}) 12... e5 13. c5 f5 {Not only gaining kingside space but also clearing
the square f7 for the knight.} 14. Rac1 Nf7 {This is a good square for the
knight. The pawn on d6 is safely defended, and in the future, the knight could
go to either e5 or g5, to sustain the attack.} 15. cxd6 ({White can keep the
tension for a while with} 15. Nd2 Bd7 16. Qa3 (16. Qb4 b6 17. cxd6 cxd6 18. Qa3
{Putting an eye on a7 but allowing the bishop's activation.} Bb5 19. Qe3 Rae8
20. Rfe1 Qb7 21. b3 e4 $15 {Eingorn,V (2580) -Wahls,M (2480) Berlin 1993 (0-1,
31) Black has neutralised White's initiative and has promising play.}) (16.
cxd6 cxd6 17. Qb3 b5 18. Rc7 Rfc8 19. Rfc1 Qd8 20. Qc2 {Tashkov,R (2239)
-Reinwald,P (2086) Belogradchik 2010 (В1/2-В1/2, 39)} a5 $11) 16... Bb5 17.
Rfe1 b6 18. Qb4 (18. b4 {Halkias,S (2385) -Gustafsson,J (2375) Yerevan 1997 
(1-0, 40)} a5 $1) 18... Bd7 19. cxb6 cxb6 20. Qa3 Rfc8 21. Rxc8+ Bxc8 22. e4
Bd7 23. Bf1 f4 24. Nc4 Qf8 25. Rc1 h6 26. Nd2 Qd8 27. Ba6 Qg5 {, with normal
counterplay for Black. Hutters,T (2465)-Khasin,A (2450) Kobanya 1991 (1/2-1/2,
61)}) 15... cxd6 16. Qc7 {The main drawback of the line with 8.Qc2 is that the
queen stands in front of the rook along the c-file.} ({Clearing the rooks'
path with} 16. Qe3 {is time consuming.} Qd8 17. Rc4 b5 18. Rc2 Bb7 19. Rfc1 Qb6
(19... Bxd5 $2 {runs into} 20. Nxe5 dxe5 21. Rd1 e4 22. Rc5) (19... a5 $5 {
, preparing ...Rc8 without losing the a7-pawn may be the most principled
continuation. The point is that} 20. Rc7 {allows} Bxd5 {already, as the rook
is hanging on c7.}) 20. Qxb6 axb6 21. Nh4 {Polak,T (2482)-Anka,E (2407) Paks
2004 (1-0, 52)} g6 22. Rc7 Rfb8 23. a3 (23. Re7 $2 Rxa2 24. Rcc7 Ra1+ 25. Bf1
Bxd5 $19) 23... Ra4 $11 24. Re7 Rc4 $1) 16... Qf6 {Threatening ...e5-e4
without allowing Nd4.} 17. e3 (17. Rc4 b5 18. Rc2 (18. Rc6 e4 19. Nd2 Qxb2 $15)
18... e4 19. Nd2 Ne5 20. Rfc1 a5 21. Qb6 Bd7 22. Rc7 Be8 23. Qd4 Bh5 {, with
adequate counterplay in Grabarczyk,M (2495)-Naiditsch,A (2532) Griesheim 2002 
(0-1, 40)}) 17... f4 {A straightforward move.} (17... g5 $5 {is also worth
mentioning.} 18. h4 {Sinkovics,P (2310)-Droulers,D Creteil 1983 (1-0, 32)} h6
$11) 18. exf4 exf4 19. Rc4 g5 20. h4 h6 {The tension has reached a peak and
the game will soon simplify to an equal yet interesting endgame.} 21. hxg5 hxg5
22. gxf4 gxf4 23. Re1 Bg4 24. Qe7 Qxe7 25. Rxe7 Bxf3 26. Bxf3 Ne5 27. Rc3 Rf7
28. Re6 Rd8 29. Kg2 Kg7 30. Be4 f3+ 31. Bxf3 Rdf8 32. Be4 {1/2-1/2 Eljanov,P 
