1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. g3 Nc6 6. Nc3 Bxc3 7. Bxc3 Ne4 8.
Rc1 {This is the absolute mainline of this system. In case of an exchange on
c3 White would be better prepared for the intrusion along the c-file (prepared
with Qc2 and Rc1), while the rook could display a certain activity along the
third rank. But unlike 8.Qc2, the last move does not attack the knight,
allowing Black to delay the exchange until he considers it convenient.} O-O $1
{The most restrictive move order.} ({If} 8... d6 9. d5 {, the pawn on g7 is
hanging, forcing} Nxc3 10. Rxc3 {, when} Nd8 11. Bg2 {transposes to a line we
prefer to avoid.}) 9. Bg2 (9. d5 Nd8 {,followed by ...d7-d6, transposes to the
mainlines.}) 9... d6 10. O-O Nxc3 {Not the only possible move order.} (10... e5
{is also viable.} 11. Be1 {The only way to try to take advantage of Black's
move order.} (11. d5 Nxc3 12. Rxc3 Nb8 {transposes below.}) 11... f5 {The main
question is whether White can do anything more constructive than block the
centre (which he did in 3 out of the 4 games with this move order.} 12. b4 {
So far the only alternative tried in practice. Cabrera Pino,A (2533)-Rios,C 
(2337) Collado Villalba 2010 (1/2-1/2, 27)} (12. d5 Nd8 {transposes to Line 18.
}) 12... a5 13. a3 axb4 14. axb4 Nxd4 15. Nxd4 exd4 16. Qxd4 Ra2 17. e3 c5 18.
Qd3 Be6 {Black has stabilised the position and is quite active. If} 19. Bxe4
fxe4 20. Qxe4 Qf7 {Black has at least enough compensation for the pawn due to
his control over the light squares.}) 11. Rxc3 e5 12. d5 ({After an early
exchange on c3, White could deviate with} 12. Re3 {, but this is not likely to
promise him much:} Qf6 13. d5 (13. dxe5 dxe5 14. b4 {can be answered with} Be6
15. b5 Nd4 $11 16. Nxe5 {leads to a draw by repetition.} Nf5 17. Re4 Nd6 18.
Re3 Nf5 19. Ng4 Qg5 20. Re4 Nd6) 13... Nb8 14. c5 Qd8 $5 $146 15. Rc3 a5 {
, and Black has won a tempo during the manoeuvres Rc3-e3-c3 and Qe7-f6-d8.} 16.
Qc2 (16. Qa4 b6 17. cxb6 cxb6 18. Rfc1 Na6 $11) 16... Na6 17. Rc1 f5 $11) 12...
Nb8 {transposes below.} 13. b4 {This way White's pawn attack has better
chances to succeed.} (13. c5 {is best answered with} a5 (13... dxc5 14. Re3 f6
15. Nd2 {offers White a strong initiative for the pawn.}) 14. cxd6 cxd6 15. Qc2
Na6 16. Rc1 (16. Nd2 {[%emt 0:00:16] transposes to Line 16.}) 16... Bd7 17. Qd2
b5 18. Re3 Qd8 19. Ne1 Qb6 20. Kh1 Rac8 $15 {Argandona Riveiro,I (2286)
-Fernandez Romero,E (2398) Mondariz 2002 (1/2-1/2, 36)}) (13. Qc2 a5 14. c5 Na6
{is likely to transpose, too.}) (13. Nd2 {is examined in Line 16.}) 13... a5 {
As we will see, Black does not have reason to refrain from this typical break,
even though it implies a pawn sacrifice.} 14. Ra3 (14. a3 {helps Black to open
the a-file for his rook at his convenience.} Na6 15. Qb3 Bd7 16. Nd2 (16. e4
Rfb8 17. c5 axb4 18. cxd6 cxd6 19. axb4 Qd8 20. Rfc1 {Shimanov,A (2535)
-Nguyen,M (2187) Stockholm 2009 (1-0, 41)} Rc8 21. Nd2 Rxc3 22. Rxc3 Nc7 23.
Bf1 Nb5 $11) (16. Rfc1 b6 17. e4 axb4 18. axb4 c5 19. dxc6 Bxc6 20. Ne1 Nc7 21.
Qb2 Ne6 22. Re3 Ra7 23. Ra1 Rc8 24. Rxa7 Qxa7 $11 {Belunek,V (2233)-Hracek,Z 
(2629) Czechia 1999 (0-1, 38) Black has excellent stability on the dark
squares.}) 16... f5 {Taking advantage of White's lack of ambition in the
centre.} (16... b6 $5) ({Without e2-e4, Black should not play for ...c7-c6:} 
16... Rfb8 17. Rfc1 axb4 18. axb4 c5 19. dxc6 bxc6 20. b5 Nc5 21. Qd1 $14 {
Ftacnik,L (2610) -Hracek,Z (2625) Ceska Trebova 1996 (1/2-1/2, 31)}) 17. c5 Bb5
18. Nc4 axb4 19. axb4 Qf6 $11) 14... Bg4 15. Nd2 {White should avoid the
exchange on f3, as this would yield Black absolute control over the dark
squares.} (15. bxa5 Bxf3 16. exf3 Na6 17. Qd2 Qf6 18. Re1 Nc5 19. h4 Rfe8 20.
Rae3 Kf8 21. R1e2 Qf5 $11 {Logothetis,S (2238)-Hickman,A (1936) West Bromwich
2004 (1/2-1/2, 30)}) 15... Na6 16. bxa5 (16. Rxa5 $5 $146 {wins a pawn but
offers Black excellent counterplay.} Nxb4 17. Rxa8 Rxa8 18. Qb3 Na6 19. Qxb7
Qd8 20. e3 Nc5 21. Qb2 Ra4 22. Rb1 g6 $5 {The pawn on a2 does not count for
much and Black has perfect coordination.}) 16... f5 17. Nb3 {White has managed
to secure his extra pawn, but his pieces are congested on the queenside, while
Black has kingside attacking chances.} f4 (17... Rf6 $5 18. f3 Bh5 19. e3 {
Arencibia Rodriguez,W (2476)-Benjamin,J (2553) Toronto 2011 (1/2-1/2, 57)} e4
$11) 18. Qd2 Rf6 19. Nc1 Raf8 20. Nd3 Bc8 {After having connected the rooks,
the bishop returns to c8, defending b7 but staying available for the attack,
too.} 21. Rc3 g5 22. Be4 Rh6 {Black is perfectly regrouped and has excellent
attacking chances, Soppe,G (2448)-Sola,R (2265) Mar del Plata 1999 (1-0, 39)} *

