1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. g3 Nc6 6. Nc3 Bxc3 7. Bxc3 Ne4 8.
Rc1 d6 9. Bg2 O-O 10. O-O Nxc3 11. Rxc3 e5 12. d5 Nb8 13. Nd2 {As mentioned in
the previous line, White can play this move slightly later, too, leading to a
transposition.} a5 14. c5 Na6 15. cxd6 cxd6 16. Qc2 (16. Nc4 {leads to a
typical situation. Black's solid position allows him to neutralize White's
initiative and slight lead in development.} Qd8 $1 {It all starts with a
counter-developing move, defending b6 and a5 and threatening ...b7-b5.} 17. Qb3
{The most principled continuation, trying to maintain the initiative.} ({
In 1991 I analysed} 17. f4 {for White, but it seems that Black does not have
any problems:} b5 18. Ne3 exf4 19. gxf4 Re8 $11 20. Nc2 (20. Qd4 Nc5 21. Re1 f5
$15) 20... Nc5 21. Nd4 b4 22. Rg3 Qf6 $15 {The weaknesses along the e-file are
more relevant than the one on c6.}) (17. a3 b5 18. Nd2 Bd7 19. Qb1 b4 20. axb4
axb4 21. Rcc1 Nc5 22. Ne4 Bf5 $17 {Khalifman,A (2615)-Adams,M (2590) Groningen
1990 (0-1, 39)}) 17... Nc5 18. Qb5 Bd7 19. Qb6 Qxb6 20. Nxb6 Ra6 21. Rxc5 {
The best try, eliminating the strongest black piece.} (21. Nc4 Rc8 22. Rfc1 Na4
23. R3c2 b5 24. Nd2 Rxc2 25. Rxc2 Nc5 26. Ne4 Nxe4 27. Bxe4 Ra7 28. Bd3 f5 $11
{Zimmerman,Y (2440)-Friedrichs,K (2148) Budapest 1999 (1/2-1/2, 60)}) 21...
Rxb6 22. Rc7 (22. Rc2 f5 23. Rfc1 a4 24. Rc7 {Vercammen,R (2038)-Rost,D (2410)
IECG email 2002 (1/2-1/2, 46)} Bb5 25. R1c2 Rf7) 22... Bb5 {Amazingly enough,
White cannot get any advantage from his control over the c-file, as his bishop
is passive.} 23. Re1 f5 24. e3 Bd3 25. b3 Rf7 26. Rc8+ Rf8 {White is best
advised to accept a draw by repetition, as if} 27. Rec1 Rxc8 28. Rxc8+ Kf7 {
, the threat ...a5-a4 followed by ...Rb1+ soon forces} 29. Rc1 Ke7 $15) 16...
b5 17. Rc1 (17. Nb3 {, as in Nebolsina,V (2302)-Zhu,C (2494) Jinan 2005 (1/2-1/
2, 49), mainly wastes time.} Qd8 18. f4 a4 19. Nc1 b4 20. Rc4 Qb6+ 21. Kh1 exf4
22. Rcxf4 Bd7 $15) (17. f4 {weakens the e-file, like in my old analysis.} b4
18. Rcf3 Bg4 19. R3f2 exf4 20. gxf4 f5 $1 $146 ({Only not} 20... Bxe2 $2 21.
Re1 Bd3 22. Rxe7 Bxc2 23. Nc4 Bb1 24. Nxd6 Bxa2 25. Nb7 $14 {Nebolsina,V (2312)
-Cherednichenko,E (2161) St Petersburg 2009 (1-0, 41)}) 21. Nc4 Nc5 22. Rc1 Nd7
$15) 17... Bd7 {White's attack has reached a dead end. It is suggestive that
in all the games White moved with his queen, trying to re-adapt his plan.} 18.
Qd1 (18. Qb1 Rab8 19. b3 f5 20. a3 b4 21. axb4 axb4 22. R3c2 Bb5 23. Nc4 Bxc4
24. Rxc4 Nc5 25. Qb2 e4 26. Rd1 {Goormachtigh,J (2277)-Dgebuadze,A (2540) Gent
2001 (0-1, 44)} f4 $15) (18. Qe4 {was played twice, but I failed to understand
White's idea after} f5 $5 $146 (18... Qd8 {is also good.} 19. a3 b4 20. axb4
axb4 21. R3c2 Bb5 22. b3 Rb8 23. Nc4 Nc5 24. Qe3 Bxc4 25. Rxc4 Re8 $11 {
Roche, J-Gasimov,R Badalona 1994 (0-1, 38)}) 19. Qe3 Qf6 $15 {The only plan
that could have scared Black is} 20. Qb6 Nc5 {Threatening to trap the queen.
After} 21. Rxc5 {White does not seem to have compensation for the exchange.}
dxc5 22. Qxf6 Rxf6 23. Rxc5 Rc8 $17) 18... f5 $5 $146 (18... a4 {actually
helps White carry out b4 later.} 19. e3 f5 20. Nf3 Rfc8 21. Bf1 Rxc3 22. Rxc3
Nc5 23. b4 axb3 24. axb3 Ne4 25. Rc7 Qd8 26. Qc2 b4 27. Kg2 $2 (27. Rb7 $1 $11)
27... Nc3 28. Rb7 Ra2 $19 {Le,Q (2583) -Naiditsch,A (2678) Beijing 2008 (0-1,
37)}) 19. e3 Qf6 $15 *

