1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. g3 Nc6 6. Nc3 Bxc3 7. Bxc3 Ne4 8.
Rc1 d6 9. Bg2 O-O 10. d5 {This plan is familiar to us from Line 14.} Nd8 {
This is a moment when the decision regarding the exchange on c3 may make a
difference.} (10... Nxc3 11. Rxc3 {I feel that with the rook on c3, this line
is less appealing for Black than the similar one in Line 14. Here are just two
examples:} Nd8 12. dxe6 Nxe6 13. O-O Bd7 14. Re1 Bc6 (14... Rab8 15. e4 b5 16.
cxb5 Rxb5 17. b3 a5 18. Bf1 Rc5 19. Rxc5 Nxc5 20. e5 $14 {Ding,L (2809)
-Rapport,R (2726) Shenzhen 2019 (1/2-1/2, 67)}) 15. e4 a5 16. b3 Rfe8 17. Rce3
Qf6 18. e5 $14 {Giri,A (2779)-Anand,V (2764) Paris 2019 (0-1, 63)}) 11. dxe6 (
11. O-O {is examined in the next line.}) 11... Nxe6 12. O-O ({White can keep
his bishop for the moment, but this means placing it on a tortuous route:} 12.
Bb4 a5 13. Ba3 f5 {Now and later this is a solid and ambitious setup at the
same time. Black is stable both on the light and the dark squares, and the
white knight is far away from d5.} 14. b3 Kh8 {This has been successfully
played by GM Loginov in a few games. I recommend taking these games as models
for the whole variation.} (14... f4 $5 $146 {looks very tempting to me, as it
prevents White from consolidating with e2-e3.} 15. O-O a4 $1 {Forcing White to
release the pressure along the a3-f8 diagonal.} (15... Bd7 $2 16. Ne5 $16) (
15... N6g5 $6 16. Nxg5 Nxg5 17. c5 $16) (15... N6c5 $5) 16. Bb2 (16. b4 N6g5
$11) 16... axb3 17. axb3 Bd7 18. Qc2 N6g5 19. Nxg5 Nxg5 20. Bxb7 Rae8 21. Bd5+
Kh8 {, with a strong kingside initiative for the pawn.}) 15. Bb2 b6 16. Nd4
Nxd4 17. Qxd4 Bb7 {I like this setup a lot. It combines the best ideas of the
Queen's-Indian and the Dutch Defence.} 18. O-O Rf6 19. Rcd1 (19. a3 Re6 20. Ra1
Rf8 21. b4 c5 {Blocking the relatively weak pawn on c4, thus avoiding c4-c5
for good and restricting the dark-squared bishop even more.} 22. Qd3 Ng5 23.
Bxb7 Qxb7 24. h4 Ne4 25. bxa5 bxa5 26. Rab1 Qe7 27. Qd5 {Lingnau,C (2395)
-Loginov,V (2540) Budapest 1994 (0-1, 39)} Rg6 $1 $146 {Threatening ...Nxg3 or
...Qxh4.} 28. h5 Nxg3 $3 29. hxg6 Nxe2+ {wins the queen or mates.}) 19... Re6
20. Bc1 (20. Rfe1 Rf8 21. Bf3 $2 f4 22. Ba1 fxg3 23. hxg3 c5 24. Qb2 Rg6 25.
Kg2 Nxg3 26. fxg3 Qg5 {0-1 Chetverik,M (2305) -Loginov,V (2540) Zalakaros 1994}
) 20... Rf8 21. Rd3 Qe8 22. a3 Qh5 ({Exchanging the bishops with} 22... Nc5 {
would absolve Black of any strategic worries:} 23. Bxb7 Nxb7 24. Bb2 Qe7 25. e3
Nc5 26. Rc3 Rg6 27. b4 Ne4 28. Rc2 axb4 29. axb4 c5 $11) 23. b4 axb4 24. axb4
Qxe2 $5 $146 (24... Rfe8 25. Ra3 R6e7 26. Ra7 {offered White some pressure in
Zakharevich,I (2415)-Loginov,V (2610) St Petersburg 1994 (1/2-1/2, 54)}) 25.
Bf3 Qc2 26. Bb2 Rg8 27. Rc1 Qa4 28. b5 Qa8 {The queen has returned back home
and White has no more than reasonable compensation for the pawn.}) 12... a5 13.
Be1 (13. b3 {is not such a big concession as to justify the exchange yet.} f5
$5 $146 (13... Nxc3 14. Rxc3 Qf6 15. Qd2 Bd7 16. e4 $1 $146 {may more or less
transpose to the Giri-Anand game above.}) (13... b6 14. Nd2 $1 Nxc3 15. Rxc3
Rb8 {may retain some pressure for White, even though the knight still needs
relocating.}) 14. Bb2 (14. e3 {prevents ...f5-f4 but spends another tempo,
justifying} Nxc3 15. Rxc3 Nc5 $11) 14... b6 $5 (14... f4 $5 {is interesting
but maybe slightly premature.} 15. Nd2 N4c5 16. Rc3 {Black's delay in
development may be a small problem.}) 15. e3 Bb7 16. Nd4 Qf7 $11 {, with
similar play as in Loginov's games.}) (13. Nd4 N6c5 14. b3 f5 $146 (14... Nxc3
{is premature as long as the rook has access to e3.} 15. Rxc3 f5 16. a3 Bd7 17.
b4 axb4 18. axb4 Ne4 19. Re3 $14 {Xu,J (2655)-Bologan,V (2655) Shanghai 2001 
(1/2-1/2, 41)}) 15. e3 (15. Bb2 f4 {offers Black excellent kingside play.} 16.
gxf4 Rxf4 17. f3 Nf6 18. Qd2 Rh4 19. Rf2 Bd7 $11) 15... Nxc3 16. Rxc3 Ne4 17.
Rc1 b6 $11) (13. Re1 {Paschall,W (2368)-Caruana,F (2409) Budapest 2006 (1/2-1/
2, 47)} f5 $5) 13... f5 14. Nd4 (14. b3 Bd7 15. Nd4 Nxd4 16. Qxd4 Bc6 17. Rc2
b6 $11 {Sriram,J (2412)-Loew,G (2185) Fuerth 2014 (1/2-1/2, 46)}) 14... N6c5 (
14... Nxd4 $5 15. Qxd4 {Dreev,A (2676) -Bocharov,D (2475) ICC INT 2002 (1-0,
39)} b6 $11) 15. e3 {Shankland,S (2498) -Benjamin,J (2556) ICC INT 2010 (0-1,
43)} b6 16. b3 Bb7 17. a3 Rae8 18. b4 axb4 19. axb4 Nd7 $11 *

