Rc1 d6 9. Bg2 O-O 10. d5 Nd8 11. O-O e5 (11... Nxc3 {is once again premature:}
12. Rxc3 e5 13. c5 f5 14. cxd6 cxd6 15. Qc2 Nf7 16. Rc7 {Black is not in time
to organize his queenside defence with ...Bd7.} Qf6 17. e3 $14) 12. Nd2 (12. c5
f5 13. cxd6 cxd6 {is likely to transpose elsewhere below.}) (12. Be1 {keeps
the bishop but offers Black some time for his regrouping and attack.} f5 13.
Nd2 Nf6 14. c5 Nf7 (14... dxc5 {is playable, too, but Black has no need to
deviate from the main plan.} 15. Nb3 e4 16. Rxc5 b6 {1/2-1/2 Hertneck,G (2605)
-Wahls,M (2540) Germany 1994}) 15. cxd6 cxd6 16. Nc4 f4 17. Bb4 {It is useful
to keep the f7-knight busy.} (17. Qd3 {wastes more than a tempo:} Bg4 18. Bb4
e4 19. Qd1 {Miles,A (2565)-Tong,Y (2355) Beijing 1993 (1-0, 53)} b5 20. Na5 Ng5
21. Nc6 Qd7 $15 22. gxf4 $2 Nh3+) 17... Bf5 18. f3 a5 $5 $146 {Black has to
fight against White's pressure on d6.} (18... Rfc8 19. e4 Bd7 20. gxf4 $14 {
left Black hanging in Khalifman,A (2635)-Wahls,M (2540) Germany 1992 (1/2-1/2,
27)}) 19. Nxa5 (19. Be1 b5) 19... Qd8 20. Nc4 b5 21. Na3 Qb6+ (21... Ra4 22.
Be1 Bd7 {also offers Black compensation.}) 22. Kh1 Qb7 {Black's better
coordination and the weakness on d5 ensure him good play despite the 
(temporarily) missing pawn.}) 12... Nxc3 {Now that White has spent a tempo on
the knight retreat, Black can finally exchange on c3.} 13. Rxc3 f5 14. c5 Nf7
15. cxd6 (15. Qb3 b6 16. c6 a5 $15) 15... cxd6 16. Qb3 (16. Qc2 {is less
effective now.} Bd7 17. Rc1 Rfc8 18. Nc4 (18. Rxc8+ $2 Rxc8 19. Qxc8+ Bxc8 20.
Rxc8+ Nd8 21. e4 {1-0 (36) Nisipeanu,L (2643)-Labib,I (2404) Dubai 2012} Qd7
22. Ra8 f4 $17) 18... b6 (18... e4 $5) 19. Qd2 {Dautov,R (2611)-Anastasian, A 
(2561) Istanbul 2003 (1-0, 44)} Qf6 $11 {[%cal Gf5f4] , possibly followed by ..
.f5-f4.}) (16. f4 {playing on two wings is likely to leave White exposed.} Bd7
17. Rc7 b6 18. e4 Rfc8 19. Qc2 exf4 20. gxf4 Qf6 $15 {Ryskin,A (2515)-Khasin,A
(2470) Kolontaevo 1994 (1/2-1/2, 32)}) 16... b6 {White seems to have some
pressure, but Black can parry the threats and retain a pleasant position.} 17.
Qa3 (17. Rfc1 Bd7 18. Qa3 Rfc8 19. Qa6 Qd8 20. Qb7 (20. e4 f4 $11) 20... Rcb8
21. Qc7 Qe8 $11 {Sykora,J (2344)-Pirhala,L (2315) ICCF email 2016 (1/2-1/2, 36)
}) 17... Bd7 18. Rc7 Rfc8 $5 $146 19. Rxa7 (19. Rfc1 Qd8 20. Rxc8 Bxc8 $11)
19... Rxa7 20. Qxa7 Qd8 21. Qa3 b5 {With excellent compensation for the pawn.
